[The World Health Organization (WHO) says African countries are running out of supplies of COVID-19 vaccines, and there is concern over the availability of further doses. So far, 7 countries have already exhausted the vaccines they received from the UN-backed Covax scheme. And some countries have not been able to use AstraZeneca vaccines before their advertised expiry date.

Deliveries of vaccine supplies under the Covax programme started in February [2021], and most countries in Africa have signed up and received vaccine doses. Some countries are also getting donations from China, Russia, the UAE and India.

The Covax initiative has so far delivered 18 million vaccine doses to 41 African countries, according to WHO. A few countries have not joined in. But WHO says Rwanda, Senegal, Ghana, Togo, Tunisia, Eswatini, and Botswana have already exhausted their initial supplies from Covax and will need to wait until early May to mid June [2021] for more. This follows a decision by the Indian government to restrict the export of vaccines following a spike in COVID-19 cases there. Most Covax supplies to African countries have been coming from India.

WHO regional director for Africa, Matshidiso Moeti, says there is hope supplies to African countries could resume in early May [2021].

The Covax programme - backed by WHO and other multilateral bodies - aims to supply 600 million doses to Africa, enough to vaccinate at least 20% of the population. But even with the initial deliveries, Africa lags far behind the rest of the world in vaccinations. The continent has only administered 2% of all the vaccine doses administered globally so far.

Some African nations got AstraZeneca vaccines donated via an arrangement between the South African-based MTN mobile communications company and the African Union. The vaccines had been bought from South Africa, which had decided against using them after purchasing them. Zimbabwe rolled out its vaccination programme using vaccines donated by China. It switched to the Johnson & Johnson vaccine after deeming it more effective against the variant [1st detected in South Africa].

But several other countries who were given these AstraZeneca doses did not manage to use them before they expired on [13 Apr 2021]. Malawi has been left with about 16 000 of doses out of 102 000, while South Sudan was left with 59 000 doses of the vaccine. Ghana and Sierra Leone were also left with some doses. WHO has now advised those countries to store the vaccines pending further guidance, rather than dispose of them.

The manufacturer, the Serum Institute of India, says the vaccines could still be used up to 3 months after the listed expiry date, although the WHO has yet to endorse this. ...-more (https://www.bbc.com/news/56100076)]

